# 🚀 Day 22 – Designing the User Experience (UX)

Welcome to **Day 22**!

Yesterday, we decided **what our app should do (the MVP)**.

Today, we're going to answer a different question:

> **"If I install this app today, what exactly will I see and tap?"**

This is called **User Experience (UX) Design**.

Professional companies like Google, Apple, and Microsoft design the user journey before they write code. We'll do the same.

---

# 🎯 Today's Goal

By the end of today, you'll have:

* A complete user journey
* A list of all screens
* An understanding of what each screen should do

No coding today—just product design.

---

# The Complete User Journey

```text
Open App
    │
    ▼
Splash Screen
    │
    ▼
Login / Register
    │
    ▼
Dashboard
    │
    ▼
Upload Blood Report
    │
    ▼
OCR Processing
    │
    ▼
AI Analysis
    │
    ▼
Save Report
    │
    ▼
Blood Report History
    │
    ▼
Compare Reports
```

This is the flow every user will follow.

---

# Screen 1 – Splash Screen

**Purpose:**
Show your app logo while the app loads.

### Contents:

* App Logo
* App Name
* "Loading..."

Example:

```text
🩸

Blood Report Analyzer

Loading...
```

---

# Screen 2 – Login / Register

### Buttons

* Login
* Create Account

Fields:

* Email
* Password

Later we can also support:

* Google Sign-In
* Apple Sign-In

---

# Screen 3 – Dashboard

This is the most important screen.

The user should immediately see:

```
Welcome, Srujan

Total Reports: 8

Latest Report:
15 July 2026

Quick Actions

+ Upload Report

View History

Compare Reports
```

---

# Screen 4 – Upload Report

User chooses:

✅ Camera

OR

✅ Gallery

OR

✅ PDF

Example:

```
Upload Blood Report

📷 Camera

🖼 Gallery

📄 PDF
```

---

# Screen 5 – OCR Processing

Instead of a blank screen, show progress.

```
Reading your report...

██████████ 75%

Extracting blood values...
```

This makes the app feel responsive.

---

# Screen 6 – Review Extracted Data

OCR isn't perfect, so let the user verify the values.

Example:

| Test       | Value |
| ---------- | ----- |
| Hemoglobin | 12.8  |
| HbA1c      | 5.9   |
| Vitamin D  | 26    |

Buttons:

* Edit
* Confirm

This improves accuracy.

---

# Screen 7 – AI Analysis

This is where your app becomes unique.

Instead of showing only numbers:

```
Hemoglobin

12.8
```

The app says:

> Your hemoglobin is within the normal range.

> HbA1c is slightly elevated and suggests prediabetes.

> Vitamin D is insufficient.

Then:

Overall Summary

```
Overall Health Score

8.5 / 10

Things Improving

✓ Hemoglobin

Needs Attention

⚠ Vitamin D
```

---

# Screen 8 – Report History

Example:

```
July 2026

Blood Test

Apollo

--------------

March 2026

Blood Test

Thyrocare

--------------

January 2026

Blood Test

Vijaya Diagnostics
```

The newest report appears first.

---

# Screen 9 – Report Details

When the user taps a report:

Show:

* Original PDF
* Extracted values
* AI explanation
* Date
* Laboratory name

---

# Screen 10 – Compare Reports

Example:

| Test       | Jan  | Mar  | Jul  |
| ---------- | ---- | ---- | ---- |
| Hemoglobin | 10.8 | 11.9 | 12.8 |
| HbA1c      | 6.8  | 6.2  | 5.7  |
| Vitamin D  | 18   | 25   | 34   |

This is one of the app's strongest features.

---

# Screen 11 – Profile

User can:

* Change password
* Update profile
* Logout

Future options:

* Delete account
* Download all reports

---

